Germination Experiment

Mario

07/12/2021

Purpose: The purpose of this experiment is to determine if cooler temperatures, as seen under shrub canopies, could be used as an indicator for the germination success of both native and exotic plant species in arid ecosystems.

Hypothesis: Temperature can directly predict the germination success of native and exotic species.

Predictions: 1) Higher temperatures will result in a lower germination rate of native plant species. 2) Invasive plant species will have a higher germination rate under all temperature treatments. 3) Higher temperatures will have a negative effect on native and invasive species biomass.

Data: All data can be access on KNB. https://knb.ecoinformatics.org/view/doi:10.5063/F1GQ6W6R

##Prep Temp Data
Layia <- read.csv("All Temp Data.csv")
Brome <- read.csv("Brome Temp Sheet.csv")
Salvia <- read.csv("Salvia Temp Sheet.csv")
Phacelia <- read.csv("Phacelia Temp Sheet.csv")

Temp <- merge(Layia, Brome, all = TRUE)
Temp <- merge(Temp, Salvia, all = TRUE)
Temp <- merge(Temp, Phacelia, all = TRUE)

write.csv(Temp, "Temp.csv")

###Clean up Temperature and determine the mean and max for each pendant.
Temp2 <- read.csv("Temp2.csv")
#Prep Germination Data and Combine With Temp Data
Germ <- read.csv("Final Germination.csv")
final <- merge(Germ, Temp2, all = TRUE)
